Q38. Explain SOLID Principles ?
ðŸ‘‰ SOLID is a set of 5 design principles in object-oriented programming.
a. S â€“ Single Responsibility Principle (SRP) : 
                      - A class should do only one job. If one class is doing multiple jobs, changes in one part may break another.
                      - eg - Controller is only responsible for API endpoints, not business logic. etc
b. O â€“ Open/Closed Principle (OCP) :
                      - Code should be open for extension, closed for modification. Means: add new features without changing old code.
                      - eg- In Spring Boot, we achieve this using interfaces + polymorphism + dependency injection.
c. L â€“ Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP) :
                      - Subclasses should be usable anywhere parent is used, without breaking behavior.
                      - In simple words â†’ Child classes should be able to replace parent classes and behave correctly.
                      - eg - In Spring Boot, we achieve it by designing interfaces with proper contracts and making sure all implementations behave consistently.
d. I â€“ Interface Segregation Principle (ISP) :
                      - Donâ€™t force classes to implement methods they donâ€™t use. Better to have small specific interfaces than one big interface.
                      - eg- In Spring Boot, we achieve it by designing modular service interfaces.
D â€“ Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP):
                      - Classes should depend on interfaces, not concrete classes. This makes code flexible and testable.
                      - eg - In Spring Boot, we achieve DIP naturally using interfaces + dependency injection.
